es and antagonisms emergent in such key political economy categories as "production," "trade," and "ecology," while also bringing out significant contemporary themes relating to "gender" and "race."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic history. 0aEconomicsxPsychological aspects. 0aEconomics-Psychological aspects. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Cultural Anthropology. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 4aPsychology : Psychoanalysis. 4aSociology : Sociology of Work. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aFridell, Gavin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSioh, Maureen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849337440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438493374423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438493374/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles